<subSubSection id="D017383B7BBB9BB24ABD701E1884F7CB" pageId="10" pageNumber="111" type="habitat">
<paragraph id="4802E1695B4F2BB5A73B2685F3B11E84" pageId="10" pageNumber="111">Habitat and range.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F69FD991EC2DD03444E8705AF6D68DA8" pageId="10" pageNumber="111">
Open forests and steppe, in light, well-drained to heavier soils. Range of the subspecies (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="87FA2DED5976C4A68E19DF34D4E406BC" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Distribution of Poa secunda subspecies in North America: subsp. secunda (yellow); subsp. juncifolia (blue)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.110.27750.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/240277" pageId="10" pageNumber="111">2B</figureCitation>
), but mostly absent from west side of the Sierra Nevada and westward. Collected once in New Mexico (
<bibRefCitation id="826307B914A0254F5742E8A1C0D7E36C" author="Soreng, RJ" journalOrPublisher="The Great Basin Naturalist" pageId="16" pageNumber="117" pagination="395 - 422" refId="B31" refString="Soreng, RJ, 1985. Poa in New Mexico, with a key to middle and southern Rocky Mountain species (Poaceae). The Great Basin Naturalist 45: 395 - 422" title="Poa in New Mexico, with a key to middle and southern Rocky Mountain species (Poaceae)." volume="45" year="1985">Soreng 1985</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
